      "FacilityID": 40510,
      "SummaryText": "ISP Synthetic Elastomers LP Port Neches Plant is a Styrene Butadiene Rubber manufacturing facility employing about 225 people. The plant was constructed in 1943 and is a producer of synthetic rubber for the manufacturing of automobile tires, shoe soles and a wide variety of rubber products. The plant follows strict  procedures for managing hazardous materials to minimize or totally eliminate releases. A trained fire brigade is maintained to respond to mergencies.                                                           The ISP Port Neches facility receives butadiene by pipline. Feedstocks are combined in reactors to produce latex. Resulting latex is coagulated, washed and dewatered. The rubber is then broken into small pieces and dried prior to packaging.             The only material managed in the ISP Port Neches plant at quantities above the RMP threshold is 1,3-Butadiene.  Butadiene is a flammable material and is a primary ingredient in rubber.  Approximately 1,000,000 lbs of butadiene is stored or processed on site in six reactor units, two recovery units and a tank farm.                                                                                                                          To prevent releases the plant has implemented numerous measures in accordance with process safety management standards, including the following: Operator training based on thorough procedures, maintining up to date process safety information, mechanical integrity testing of equipment in butadiene service, conducting process hazards analysis and follow through with recommendations, managing changes in the proces so that procedures, training and PSI are all updated and conducting compliance audits and incident investigations.                                                                                                   The plant, under previous ownership, has experienced one accident which meets the criteria of the RMP accident history.  In September 2002 an explosion occu"
    },
    {
      "ESSeqNum": 1,
      "FacilityID": 40510,
      "SummaryText": "rred inside a butadiene line in the recovery portion of the plant.  The explosion resulted in the rupture of another butadiene line causing in turn a butadiene release of approximately 3500 lbs and a fire. There were no associated deaths or injuries.  Cost of the damage was approximately $2,000,000.                                                                                                                      A major improvement under way involving safety is the new butadiene blending system. This new system replaces old pipe, reduces the number of valves and pumps and reduces the quantity of recycle butadiene on site."
    }
  ]
